player.seasonOutlook: Agholor signed with the Patriots after enjoying a bit of a resurgence during his lone season with the Raiders. Following an up-and-down five years in Philadelphia, Agholor put together a strong 48-896-8 receiving line on 81 targets last season. He struggled with drops (seven) but was heavily targeted down field (15.4 aDOT was third highest among WRs) and answered the bell with plenty of explosive plays (his 18.7 YPR ranked second and his 11.1 YPT fourth). Agholor is entering his seventh NFL season at age 28 and has yet to post a top-20 fantasy campaign (he has finished better than 34th once: 2017). Agholor very well could lead New England in targets, but consistent flex production may be a lot to ask in a run-heavy scheme that will throw to its RBs and TEs often. Agholor is a fine bench option.

Gage entered the 2020 season as an intriguing deep sleeper, and he quietly paid off for those who took a shot. Gage ranked 22nd at WR in targets and finished 37th in fantasy points despite finding the end zone only four times. Oddly, he was even better during five full games with Julio Jones and Calvin Ridley, handling a 20% target share and ranking 15th at WR in fantasy. With Jones now in Tennessee, Gage is now the favorite for No. 2 duties. On the other hand, Gage is a short-area target who adds little after the catch. His efficiency numbers have been very poor the past two seasons and Atlanta won't throw as often in new coach Arthur Smith's run-first, TE-friendly scheme. The 25-year-old's standing on the depth chart is enough to warrant a bench spot.

Crowder has been one of the league's busiest wide receivers during his two seasons with the Jets, ranking top-13 in average target share in both 2019 and 2020. The heavy usage allowed Crowder a WR26 fantasy campaign in 2019, and he was WR14 during 12 active weeks in 2020. Despite the success, Crowder is a good bet for a step back in 2021. His usage and production declined as last season progressed (11.5 targets per game in his first four games, 5.5 in his final eight), New York will have a new coaching staff and rookie QB (Zach Wilson), and the Jets added Corey Davis, Elijah Moore and Keelan Cole to the WR room. Crowder is a short-range target in a low-scoring offense. The 28-year-old is a PPR flex in 12-team leagues.

Marshall was selected by Carolina with the 59th overall pick of April's draft. The LSU star is tall (6-foot-3, 205 pounds) and young (21 years old) with good speed and a large catch radius. He is terrific in contested situations and a threat with the ball in his hands. Mitchell has experience inside and out, having aligned in the slot 83% of the time in 2020. That's notable as Robby Anderson and DJ Moore primarily worked on the perimeter last season with Samuel in the slot. Expect Marshall to step right in as the No. 3 WR in an offense that supported three top-25 fantasy WRs in 2020. If Sam Darnold plays solid ball, Marshall could sneak into fantasy relevance. Grab him with a late pick.

Moore was selected by Arizona with the 49th overall pick of April's draft. The Purdue product is a 5-foot-7, 180-pound short-area, slot receiver. He led the nation with 114 receptions as a true freshman in 2018 before combining to play eight games due to injury and a COVID-related opt out over the past two seasons. Moore aligned in the slot 88% of the time during his time at Purdue, and his 5.2 aDOT and 11.0 YPR are lowest in this year's rookie class during that span. Expect the speedy Moore (reported 4.28 40) to find his way to a slot/rusher/returner role in the pros, though short-term playing time may be limited with DeAndre Hopkins, A.J. Green and Christian Kirk also on the depth chart. Moore is a shaky bet for immediate flex production, but his pedigree in a good offense makes him worth a late flier.

Bernard signed with Buccaneers after eight seasons with the Bengals. Bernard ranked 26th among RBs with 171 touches last season and, while that may not seem like much, he totaled 174 during the 2018-19 seasons. Bernard's production was all over the map, however, as he reached 20 fantasy points in four games after Joe Mixon's Week 6 season-ending injury, but was in single digits the other six weeks. Bernard is still a capable receiver (81% catch rate, 6.1 YPT in 2020), but has struggled badly as a rusher recently (his 3.4 YPC is fourth worst and his 1.5 YAC eighth worst among 57 RBs with 200-plus carries since 2018). The 29-year-old will see the occasional touch, but Leonard Fournette and Ronald Jones II will handle most of the work in Tampa Bay. Bernard belongs on waivers.

Coleman signed with the Jets and will compete for work with fourth-round rookie Michael Carter. Following a promising start to his career during four seasons in Atlanta, Coleman missed 10 games and didn't live up to expectations during the past two seasons in San Francisco. The 2015 third-round pick was a top-22 fantasy RB in three consecutive seasons spanning 2016-18, but fell to 39th in 2019 and was reduced to only 87 yards on 32 touches in eight games in 2020. The 28-year-old is best-served for situational duties and will only join the flex radar if injuries force him into a starting role. He's worth a late flier simply due to his situation.

Ingram signed with Houston during the offseason after eight seasons in New Orleans and two with Baltimore. Ingram was a fantasy starter as recently as 2019 (1,265 yards and 15 TDs on 228 touches), but fell off the map in 2020, often designated as a healthy scratch down the stretch. Ingram is now 31 years old and will be more of a veteran presence than a consistent contributor in a backfield that also includes David Johnson and Phillip Lindsay. Ingram may steal the occasional touchdown, but even if injuries were to strike, it's unlikely he'd handle enough work for RB2 production. Ingram doesn't need to be drafted.

Green signed with Arizona after spending his first 10 NFL seasons in Cincinnati. Green is coming off what was easily the worst season of his career, ranking 27th in routes and 26th in targets among WRs, but outside the top 60 in receptions, yardage and TDs. His 44% catch rate, 4.9 YPT and 1.8 RAC all ranked dead last, though 25% of balls thrown his way were off target (seventh highest). Perhaps Green will bounce back opposite heavily targeted DeAndre Hopkins, but it's hard to get too excited, considering he's now 33 years old, last season's performance and his shaky durability (missed at least six games in three of the past five seasons). Despite the concerns, Green's resume and starting gig in a good offense are enough to make him worth a late flier.

Cobb was traded back to Green Bay after posting a 38-441-3 receiving line in 10 games with Houston last season. A fantasy standout during his early years, Cobb has missed at least one game each of the past five seasons, including six missed in 2020 and seven in 2018. He failed to clear four TDs during any of those campaigns. Cobb continues to dominate with the ball in his hands, as he's never finished a season in which he handled 50-plus targets lower than 17th in RAC, but his role and shaky durability have prevented him from posting a top-30 fantasy season since 2014. The 31-year-old has a path to a substantial role as Aaron Rodgers' hand-picked slot receiver, but his limitations make him no more than a PPR bench option.

Few players have enjoyed as high a target floor as Shepard over the past few seasons. Shepard has seen at least six targets in 25 of his past 27 games, the exceptions being a five-target outing and a four-target game he left injured. Unfortunately, the usage hasn't led to much fantasy success, as he's yet to finish a season better than 30th in fantasy points. The culprits? Injuries (missed at least four games in three of the past four seasons) and a short-area role (career 9.1 aDOT) that doesn't allow much work near the end zone (12 TDs over the past four seasons). The 27-year-old is headed for a reduced role (likely a significant one) in 2021 with Kenny Golladay and first-round pick Kadarius Toney now in the mix. Shepard will remain involved but is best valued as a low-ceiling bench option.

Davis was very busy as a fourth-round rookie last season, playing 754 snaps, which ranked fifth among rookie WRs and 34th overall at the position. The UCF product benefited from John Brown's injuries, as well as a Bills offense that was second pass-heaviest in the NFL and ranked first in three-plus WR sets (94%) and second in four-plus WR sets (17%) when passing. Brown is gone and Emmanuel Sanders is in behind Stefon Diggs and Cole Beasley, but keep in mind that Davis played 68% of the snaps and handled 19% of the team's air yards as a 21-year-old rookie. Davis ranked top-5 in YPR (17.1) and aDOT (15.1), and his role in Buffalo's Josh Allen-led offense may increase in 2021. He's a fine late-round flier.

Sanders is back for his 12th NFL season and will be suiting up for Buffalo. Sanders is now 34 years old and has missed at least two games three of the past four seasons, but he's still been effective when healthy. He's finished in the 90th percentile in catch rate and 70th percentile in YPT each of the past three seasons despite playing for three different teams. He's delivered five top-30 fantasy campaigns over the past seven seasons. Sanders now joins a Bills offense that was second pass-heaviest in the NFL and ranked first in three-plus WR sets (94%) and second in four-plus WR sets (17%) when passing last season. Sanders figures to share No. 3 duties with Gabriel Davis behind Stefon Diggs and Cole Beasley. He is worth a bench spot in deep leagues.

Ebron's 2020 season - his first with Pittsburgh - started slowly, but he quietly finished 10th or better at the position in routes, targets, receptions and OTD, while landing 12th in fantasy points per game. Ebron posted three games with 11-plus targets after Week 11 and was fantasy's No. 8 TE after Week 2. Ebron played 73% of the snaps when active last season and his primary competition for work is rookie Pat Freiermuth in a Steelers' offense that has posted a TE target share of at least 15% each of the past 12 seasons. Ebron is likely to be undervalued in 2021 drafts, as the 28-year-old very much as back-end TE1 upside in the Steelers' pass-heavy scheme.

Kmet was the first TE selected in the 2020 draft (43rd overall) and is positioned for a bigger role in his second season with the Bears. After totaling 14 targets during his first 11 NFL games, Kmet averaged 5.7 per game during his final six games. The Notre Dame product reached six targets in four of those games and fell below four only once, averaging a healthy 17% target share during the span. Kmet turned the usage into a weak 23-165-1 receiving line, but 23% of balls thrown his way were off target (sixth-highest among TEs). More downfield (6.3 aDOT) and goal line work (one end zone target) would be nice, but his target volume and 88% snap share suggest better days are ahead. Even if Jimmy Graham sticks around, 22-year-old Kmet should be viewed as a TE2 with breakout potential.

Ertz is entering his ninth NFL season in search of a rebound after struggling with injuries, inefficiency and a shaky supporting cast during a very disappointing 2020. Ertz had ripped off five consecutive top-nine fantasy campaigns (including three straight top-four seasons) prior to missing five games and falling to 31st in 2020. Ertz played 81% of the snaps and handled a generous 19% of the targets during 11 active weeks, but 30% of balls thrown his way were off target (second highest), which led to a position-worst 49% catch rate and horrific 4.6 YPT (second worst). Ertz is "only" 30 years old, so a rebound is possible, but it's also reasonable to think his days as a TE1 are over, especially with Dallas Goedert likely ahead of him on the depth chart. Consider Ertz a mid-range TE2.

Roethlisberger is back for his 18th season as the Steelers' starting QB. After missing nearly the entire 2019 campaign, Roethlisberger bounced back with a high-volume season that saw him finish third in the league in both pass attempts and completions, but seventh in touchdowns and 16th in passing yards. Roethlisberger's 6.3 YPA was the worst of his career, though certainly influenced by a league-high 34 drops. Roethlisberger has a very good group of targets, but the Steelers' line took a big hit during the offseason and the 39-year-old is a zero as a rusher (11 rushing yards in 2020). Roethlisberger has finished better than ninth at QB only once over the past six years and is best valued as a mid-range QB2 in 2021.

The Buccaneers will enter 2021 with their entire starting lineup from last season's Super Bowl champion squad. In fact, all 19 players who played at least 59 defensive snaps for Tampa Bay last season remain on the roster. The 2020 unit ranked no lower than eighth in INTs, forced fumbles, sacks, yardage allowed or points allowed. The Bucs have a good secondary led by Carlton Davis and terrific duos at DT (Vita Vea, Ndamukong Suh), edge (Shaquil Barrett, Jason Pierre-Paul) and LB (Lavonte David, Devin White). Tampa Bay's D/ST is fresh off back-to-back top-10 fantasy campaigns and is well positioned for a leap to the elite in 2021.

Pittsburgh entered 2020 with the league's best defense and it showed up in fantasy. The Steelers' D/ST posted its second consecutive second-place finish after back-to-back top-eight campaigns the two seasons prior. Incredibly, the Steelers have now led the NFL in sacks in four straight seasons. They've also finished top-two in INTs and top-five in both yardage and points allowed each of the past two seasons. Most of the defensive core returns in 2021, with Steven Nelson, Mike Hilton and Bud Dupree the notable exceptions. Not much was done to replace the trio, but Devin Bush will be back from a torn ACL and the unit remains loaded with talent, including T.J. Watt, Minkah Fitzpatrick, Cameron Hayward, Stephon Tuitt and Joe Haden. Pittsburgh's D/ST should be one of the first units picked in your draft.

Another year, another dominant performance by the Ravens' defense. Baltimore's unit posted its fifth straight top-five fantasy campaign in 2020. The Ravens' defense has ranked no worse than third in points allowed each of the past three seasons and has a massive 22 TDs during its past four campaigns. Baltimore led the NFL with 22 forced fumbles in 2020. It was a fairly quiet offseason for the unit, but 12 of the top 13 players in terms of 2020 defensive snaps remain on the roster. A loaded secondary led by Marlon Humphrey and Marcus Peters and a terrific interior defensive line led by Calais Campbell and Derek Wolfe helps anchor one of fantasy's top D/ST options in 2021.

It's been a long time since Washington's D/ST was fantasy-relevant, but the unit posted its first top-15 campaign in more than a decade with a fourth-place finish in 2020. Washington finished no lower than sixth in INTs, sacks, yardage allowed and points allowed. The anchor of the unit is a defensive line that includes four first-round picks (Chase Young, Montez Sweat, Jonathan Allen, Daron Payne), but the secondary added some juice during the offseason with star CB William Jackson joining Kendall Fuller and Landon Collins and the team spent its first-round pick on LB Jamin Davis. Washington's defense returns nine of its top 10 players in snaps from 2020 and is one of the league's best on paper. This is a starting-caliber fantasy D/ST.

The 49ers D/ST entered the 2020 season fresh off a third-place finish the season prior and with one of the league's best defenses on paper. Unfortunately, injuries struck early and often and the unit fell to a 13th-place finish. Despite the step back, the 49ers still managed eight top-10 fantasy weeks, which was seventh most. They finished top five in yardage allowed for the second year in a row, but fell to 21st in forced turnovers (20) and 22nd in sacks (30). Expect a bounce back in 2021 with a healthy Nick Bosa (and perhaps Dee Ford) set to rejoin the likes of Arik Armstead, Fred Warner, Jason Verrett, Jimmie Ward and 2020 first-round pick Javon Kinlaw. Losing defensive coordinator Robert Saleh hurts, but the talent is here for the 49ers' D/ST to return to top-10 status in fantasy.

Sean McDermott continues to get the job done, as the Buffalo D/ST has now ripped off three consecutive top-nine fantasy campaigns. The Bills have finished no lower than eighth in both INTs and forced fumbles each of the past four seasons but have struggled to generate sacks during the stretch and fell outside the top 13 in both yardage and points allowed last season. On paper, this is a good unit, with Tre'Davious White, Jordan Poyer and Micah Hyde leading a solid secondary and Jerry Hughes and Matt Milano joining youngsters Tremaine Edmunds and Ed Oliver in the front seven. The unit's top-10 players in 2020 snaps all remain on the roster. Buffalo's D/ST is a solid starting option in fantasy.

Vic Fangio is one of the league's top defensive minds, but it has yet to translate to Denver's D/ST, as the unit has posted finishes of 19th and 22nd over the past two seasons. The Broncos finished outside the top 20 in INTs and forced fumbles both seasons, but even without Von Miller, leaped to ninth in sacks (42) in 2020. Expect things to improve in 2021. Miller will return after missing all of 2020, Kyle Fuller, Ronald Darby and first-round pick Patrick Surtain II were added to a very strong secondary and Denver's top 10 players in 2020 snaps remain on the roster. The talent is solid across the board thanks to the likes of Justin Simmons, Kareem Jackson, Bryce Callahan, Bradley Chubb, Dre'Mont Jones and Shelby Harris, so we should expect Denver to, at least, leap into the top 10 at D/ST this season.

The post-Tom Brady Patriots took a big step back last season, so it may surprise you that their D/ST still managed its eighth top-12 fantasy campaign over the past nine seasons. The unit obviously fell off from its dominant first-place finish in 2019, but still showed well in several departments. The Patriots' 18 INTs paced the NFL for the second consecutive season and they ranked second in D/ST TDs (four) and seventh in points allowed (341). A majority of last season's unit is back for 2021 and a ton of talent was added to the mix, including Kyle Van Noy, Matthew Judon, Henry Anderson, Davon Godchaux and Jalen Mills. Dont'a Hightower (opt out) also returns to a unit with a loaded secondary and a ton of depth. Bill Belichick has rebuilt what should be a top-10 fantasy D/ST.

The Rams' D/ST was the top-scoring unit by 12 fantasy points last season and has now posted finishes of fourth, third, ninth and first during Sean McVay's four seasons with the team. During its dominant 2020 campaign, the Rams allowed the fewest yards and points, while also ranking second in sacks (53) and D/ST TDs (four). Despite the success, this unit could be in for a step back in 2021. Defensive coordinator Brandon Staley departed for the Chargers and Michael Brockers, John Johnson III and Troy Hill (the latter two finished 1-2 in snaps last season) left via free agency. Of course, star power remains in the form of Jalen Ramsey and Aaron Donald, in addition to solid contributors like Leonard Floyd and Darious Williams. Consider the Rams D/ST a midrange starting option.

The Browns' defense: an NFL juggernaut? It's not as crazy as it sounds. Cleveland's D/ST hasn't finished a season better than 15th in fantasy points since 2001 (seriously), but did take a step forward in 2020 by ranking second in forced fumbles (17) and near mid-pack in most other categories. Of course, the real key here is what is now a loaded unit on paper following an offseason overhaul. Gone are eight of the defense's top 10 players in terms of 2020 snaps, but Myles Garrett and Denzel Ward are the exceptions and newcomers include Jadeveon Clowney, John Johnson III, Troy Hill, Takk McKinley, Malik Jackson, Anthony Walker, first-round pick Greg Newsome II and 2020 COVID opt-out Andrew Billings. Youngsters Grant Delpit and Greedy Williams could also be back from injuries. This is a loaded unit and potential top-10 fantasy D/ST.

The Colts' D/ST was one of the breakout units of 2020, finishing third in fantasy points, which marks its first top-12 finish since 2013. Indianapolis' 12 top-10 weeks and six TDs led the league. The unit finished no lower than 12th in INTs, forced fumbles, sacks, yardage allowed and points allowed. The Colts did lose a few solid contributors in Anthony Walker, Denico Autry, Justin Houston and Malik Hooker during the offseason, which leaves them with a few voids, but stars DeForest Buckner, Darius Leonard, Kenny Moore and Xavier Rhodes remain in place. This D/ST figures to take a step back in 2021, but will be a streaming option when the matchup is right.

The Vikings' D/ST was one of the biggest disappointments of 2020, plummeting to a 27th-place finish after six consecutive seasons finishing 13th or better (including three top-fives the past four years). The big culprits were sacks, yardage allowed and points allowed, as Minnesota finished 27th or worse in all three categories while also failing to score a single D/ST TD. On the plus side, the Vikings' 15 INTs ranked seventh. Expect defensive mastermind Mike Zimmer to lead this group to a better showing in 2021. Patrick Peterson, Dalvin Tomlinson, Mackenzie Alexander and Xavier Woods were added to a unit that will have Michael Pierce, Danielle Hunter and Anthony Barr back after the trio missed all or most of 2020. Add Eric Kendricks and Harrison Smith to the mix and Minnesota's D/ST has the talent to leap back into weekly starting consideration.

Butker opened his NFL career with three consecutive top-seven fantasy campaigns, which included a first-place finish in 2019. In yet another shining example of why you never reach on a kicker in fantasy, he fell to 11th and managed only five top-10 weeks in 2020. Butker hit a career-high 92.6% of his FG attempts (25 of 27), but missed six of 54 extra points (88.9%). Despite the "down" season, Butker remains the kicker for an elite, Patrick Mahomes-led Chiefs offense, which makes the 26-year-old one of the most-appealing kickers at a position overloaded with randomness.

Tucker has played eight seasons in the NFL and has finished 11th or better at the position in all eight. However, as good as he's been, he's never finished a season in the top spot. His eighth-place finish in 2020 was his worst finish since 2015. Volume was the primary culprit, as he matched a career low with 29 FG attempts (set in 2019), but his conversion rate of 89.7% was also his lowest since 2015. On the plus side, he made 52 of 53 extra points. Baltimore hasn't been as reliant on Tucker with Lamar Jackson under center (as opposed to the Joe Flacco era), but the 31-year-old is still the best in the business. He remains a strong fantasy option.

Since the start of the 2017 season, Gano has converted 74 of 78 FG attempts. That 94.9% hit rate trails only Josh Lambo for best in the NFL and, if we adjust for distance, Gano is the league's most accurate kicker during the span. Gano is coming off the best season of his lengthy career, having converted 31 of 32 field goal attempts in 2020. Despite a struggling offense that tied for last in touchdowns, Gano's 32 FG attempts were 12th most. Gano is now 34 years old, but the combination of his elite accuracy and an improved Giants offense makes him a viable starter in fantasy.

Myers was one of the best kickers in the NFL last season, nailing all 24 of his FG attempts. His accuracy has been inconsistent throughout his career, but he's now had two great seasons in the past three years (33-of-36 in 2018). He actually came out slow in 2020 with five consecutive games in single digits, but was the No. 2 kicker from Week 7 on. His 11 top-10 weeks for the season were most at the position. The 30-year-old is in a good spot as the kicker in a Russell Wilson-led offense, so he's back on the starting radar in 2021.

McManus fell just short of back-to-back top-10 fantasy campaigns last season, but it wasn't for a lack of strong play. McManus was asked to attempt an NFL record 15 field goals of 50-plus yards (he tied an NFL record by making 10). His seemingly weak 82.4 FG% for the season was actually well above his 72.8% expected rate based on distance and was actually the most efficient season of his career (he was 18-of-19 on FG attempts under 50 yards). The 30-year-old is one of the best in the business and benefits from nine games in the thin, mile-high air this season. He's a fine fantasy starter.

Sanders is fantasy's reigning top-scoring kicker and has quietly emerged as one of the league's best at the position. The 2018 seventh-rounder was terrific last season, hitting 36 of 39 FG attempts (92.3%), and was the only kicker who played the whole season to make 100% of his extra-point attempts (36 of 36). He finished as a top-10 fantasy kicker 10 times last season, which tied for second most. Sanders is locked in long term in Miami after signing a five-year, $22 million extension during the offseason. He has a decent shot to repeat as a starting-caliber fantasy kicker.

Koo's NFL career got off to a slow start when he was cut after only four games with the Chargers back in 2017. After bouncing around the country for a few years, including a stop in the AAF, Koo finally found a home with the Falcons in 2019. Since that point, he's been one of the league's best kickers, nailing 60 of his 65 FG attempts (92.3%) and 48 of 53 extra points (90.6%). In 2020, Koo attempted 39 field goals (second most in the league) and converted 37 (most) for an impressive 94.9% conversion rate. He delivered 10 top-10 fantasy weeks (tied for second most) en route to finishing second among kickers in fantasy points. The 27-year-old is a solid fantasy starter.

Gay was selected by Tampa Bay in the fifth round of the 2019 draft and was fantasy's No. 4 kicker as a rookie. However, his "success" was very volume based, as he missed eight of his 35 FG attempts and five of his 48 extra points. Gay was waived prior to the 2020 season, but landed with the Rams as a late-season injury replacement. He went on to make 14-of-16 FG attempts and all 16 PAT tries while posting the sixth-most fantasy points during seven active weeks. The 27-year-old isn't a sure thing, but he's in a good spot as the kicker in a Sean McVay offense. He'll be a fine fantasy starter if he hangs on to the job.

"Greg the Leg" has finished as a top-12 fantasy kicker each of the past four seasons, which includes the top spot in 2017 and a fifth-place finish in 2020, his first with Dallas. Zuerlein made "only" 82.9% of his FG attempts (34 of 41) last season, but that's a bit misleading, as six of the seven misses were on tries from 50-plus yards away (an area he's generally been good). The 41 attempts were also most in the NFL last season. Zuerlein's accuracy has been all over the map throughout his career, but he's set up nicely as the kicker in a loaded and high-volume offense in Dallas. The 33-year-old is a fine fantasy starter.

Bass was fantasy's No. 4 kicker as a rookie in 2020. The sixth-round pick's career started slowly, as he managed seven or fewer points in his first six games, but he finished strong with a position-best 116 fantasy points after Week 6. He benefited from the Bills' high-scoring offense, as his 59 extra-point attempts were second most and his 34 field goal attempts seventh most among kickers. Bass' field goal accuracy was slightly below average (82.4%), but the 24-year-old will surely be busy again in the same situation in 2021. He's a back-end starting kicker option in most formats.

St. Brown was selected by Detroit in the fourth round of April's draft. The former USC star is 5-foot-11, 197 pounds and aligned in the slot on 69% of his routes at USC. St. Brown's usage was interesting, as he was sent on a vertical route 14% of the time over the past three seasons (lowest in this year's class), instead relying more on hook (25%) and out routes (15%). That led to a below-average aDOT (10.0) but also an underwhelming 4.6 RAC. St. Brown's landing spot is what has him on the immediate fantasy radar, as he joins Breshad Perriman, Tyrell Williams and Quintez Cephus atop the depth chart. The rookie very well could lead that group in targets if he's up to the task. Take a late-round flier.

Booker signed with the Giants after spending his first four seasons in Denver and 2020 in Las Vegas. Booker hasn't played more than 30% of the snaps in a season since 2016, though he was serviceable off the bench behind Josh Jacobs in 2020. Booker averaged 4.55 YPC (1.84 YAC) on 93 carries and added 84 yards on 21 targets (4.0 YPT). The 29-year-old is a replacement-level player, but is positioned as Saquon Barkley's clear backup in New York. Booker has no standalone value but could handle 15 or so touches per game if Barkley misses time. Consider him as a Barkley insurance policy in deep leagues.

Evans appeared in six games and played 34 snaps after being drafted in the third round of the 2020 draft. Buried behind lead back Derrick Henry and, at times, Jeremy McNichols, Evans produced 81 yards and one TD on 16 touches. The 5-foot-10, 203-pound back has 4.41 wheels and is a capable receiver. He'll look to carve out a change-of-pace role behind Henry in 2021, but he won't be close to standalone value. Of course, should Henry miss time, Evans will immediately leap to the RB2 discussion, making him an intriguing deep-league insurance option.

Murray is back in New Orleans as the early-down complement to the more-versatile Alvin Kamara. The role has allowed Murray 8.2 carries and 1.8 targets per game during outings in which both were active over the past two seasons. That's obviously not much and resulted in a grand total of three weekly finishes better than 25th (one better than 16th). Murray obviously lacks standalone value, though it's worth noting he put up 307 yards and four TDs on 62 touches during two games Kamara missed with an injury in 2019. Murray is now 31 years old and, though his stock is down with Drew Brees retired, he remains one of fantasy's top insurance policies.

The Patriots selected Stevenson in the fourth round of April's draft. If you're a fan of elusiveness, tackle breaking and post-contact production, Stevenson is your guy. The Oklahoma product is oversized at 6-foot, 229 pounds, but is still quick and shifty. Granted his sample size is very small (165 carries, 34 targets over 19 career games), but Stevenson's 4.8 YAC and 2.9 forced missed tackle rate during the span are both tops in this year's class. As if that wasn't enough, Stevenson averaged 12.8 receiving yards after the catch (RAC) on his 28 career receptions, which is fourth-best in this class. On the other hand, Stevenson is one of the oldest backs in this class (23) and doesn't have a clear path to short-term touches with Damien Harris, J.J. Taylor and James White in the mix. Stevenson is worth drafting in dynasty only.

Cohen returns as Chicago's change-of-pace and primary receiving back after tearing his ACL in Week 3 last season. His 190-pound frame has limited him to no more than 99 carries in a single season and a grand total of four carries inside the 5-yard line. However, 70-plus catches in both 2018 and 2019 helped him to fantasy finishes of 11th in 2018 and 27th in 2019. During his first three seasons in the NFL, Cohen ranked fourth among backs in both targets (261) and receptions (203). The 26-year-old's efficiency was poor in 2019 (3.3 YPC, 4.4 YPT), he didn't impress pre-injury in 2020 (115 yards on 20 touches) and, following David Montgomery's breakout, he'll remain very limited as a rusher and at the goal line. Cohen has some PPR flex value in deep leagues, but his ceiling is low.

Penny has played 14% of the Seahawks' offensive snaps since being drafted in the first round of the 2018 draft. Injuries have been the culprit, as he was limited to 10 games in 2019 and only three in 2020. The good news is that Penny has shown well when active, averaging 5.1 YPC (sixth-best among 77 RBs with 150-plus carries since 2018) and 2.0 YAC (12th-best) on 161 career carries and 6.9 YPT on 23 career targets. The 25-year-old has some post-hype appeal, but he remains behind Chris Carson on Seattle's depth chart, so he's worth no more than a late-round flier in deeper leagues.
